Below is a clean Spring Batch implementation for your case:

✔ Multiple CSV files in S3
✔ Batch runs hourly
✔ Tasklet → get file list
✔ Chunk step → read CSV and insert into DB
✔ Tasklet → mark/move processed file

This is a typical enterprise batch pipeline.

⸻

1️⃣ Job Configuration

@Configuration
@EnableBatchProcessing
public class BatchConfig {

    @Autowired
    private JobBuilderFactory jobBuilderFactory;

    @Autowired
    private StepBuilderFactory stepBuilderFactory;

    @Bean
    public Job csvImportJob(Step listFilesStep,
                            Step processFileStep,
                            Step moveFileStep) {

        return jobBuilderFactory.get("csvImportJob")
                .start(listFilesStep)
                .next(processFileStep)
                .next(moveFileStep)
                .build();
    }
}


⸻

2️⃣ Step 1 — Tasklet (List S3 Files)

@Component
public class S3ListFilesTasklet implements Tasklet {

    private final S3Client s3Client = S3Client.builder().build();

    @Override
    public RepeatStatus execute(StepContribution contribution,
                                ChunkContext chunkContext) {

        List<String> files = new ArrayList<>();

        ListObjectsV2Request request = ListObjectsV2Request.builder()
                .bucket("my-bucket")
                .prefix("csv/")
                .build();

        ListObjectsV2Response response = s3Client.listObjectsV2(request);

        for (S3Object object : response.contents()) {
            if (object.key().endsWith(".csv")) {
                files.add(object.key());
            }
        }

        chunkContext.getStepContext()
                .getStepExecution()
                .getJobExecution()
                .getExecutionContext()
                .put("files", files);

        return RepeatStatus.FINISHED;
    }
}

Step configuration:

@Bean
public Step listFilesStep(S3ListFilesTasklet tasklet) {
    return stepBuilderFactory.get("listFilesStep")
            .tasklet(tasklet)
            .build();
}


